Your Turn 1

Run the code on the slide to make a graph. Pay strict attention to spelling, capitalization, and parentheses!

## Your Turn 1
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

Your Turn 2

Add color, size, alpha, and shape aesthetics to your graph. Experiment.

## Your Turn 2
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

Your Turn 3

Replace this scatterplot with one that draws boxplots. Use the cheatsheet. Try your best guess.

## Your Turn 3
ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy))

Your Turn 4

Make a histogram of the hwy variable from mpg.

## Your Turn 4
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = hwy), binwidth = 2)

Your Turn 5

Make a density plot of hwy colored by class.

## Your Turn 5
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_density(mapping = aes(x = hwy, color = class))

Your Turn 6

Make a bar chart hwy colored by class.

## Your Turn 6
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = class, fill = class))

Your Turn 7

Predict what this code will do. Then run it.

## Your Turn 7
ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(displ, hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Your Turn 9

Save the last plot and then locate it in the files pane.

## Your Turn 9
ggsave("my-plot.png")
